commit.message:
bluelet: catch ECONNRESET

When ncmpcpp quits after an error it causes a "connection reset by peer"
exception, also known as ECONNRESET (104) in errno terms. In Python
2 this is mapped to a `socket.error` and in Python 3 this is
  `ConnectionResetError` which is thankfully a subclass of the
  `socket.error` exception class.

Merge pull request #6 from wezzman/master

Join bug fix.

Update bluelet.py

Fixed bug where joining an already exited coroutine blocks indefinitely.
Added tag v0.2.0 for changeset dcbab156f675
detect attempts to use closed sockets

abstract socket connections with pickle channels

Just playing around a little with abstract "channels" that pickle and unpickle
objects for more abstract communication between threads.

set up both ends of an IPC channel a priori

Now, a socket for IPC can be set up by a "parent" thread and then passed to
other processes as a parameter.

This entailed adding a "join" functionality to the bluelet scheduler, which
suspends a coroutine until a previously-spawned child coroutine finishes. This
is useful in general.
initial experiments with IPC among coroutines
make HTTPD example a little more useful
_event_select(): handle the case where a socket is readable and writable at the same time.
